"England and Australia really know how to present a Test match. It begins with the architecture. Unlike the concrete monsters that seem the norm in India, most grounds in England and Australia are warm, open, intimate – even the cavernous MCG and buttoned-up Lord’s. No spiked barrier-fences separating spectator from action, inclusive spaces, kids playing on the field during lunch and tea, bat-making workshops, museums that chronicle the ground’s lore, live jazz bands, and what not. But in the main – in stark contrast to the attitude in India – there’s an attempt to make things as comfortable as possible. Convenient commutes, organised queues, and working toilets, cases in point."

Would his soon-to-be-released memoir match these standards?

"I don’t want to send throbbing red hearts to strange men, eminent academics though they might be. In my book, a heart-shaped sign, red in colour, symbolises passionate love. I can see myself sending that heart to my spouse or a tall, dark stranger I want to woo. At a stretch, maybe to my sister or daughter, who would both think I had lost my mind. I can even send it to a puppy dog or an unknown tiger cub but I find it really, really hard to send that heart to Penguin Books, who have just tweeted about acquiring the rights to the next Amitav Ghosh novel, or to a famous feminist activist who is tweeting about misogyny."
link_name: My love is like a red, red heart
